wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-size\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image\" src=\"https://confluence/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-7%2016%3A41%3A42.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" height=\"400\" data-image-src=\"/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-7%2016%3A41%3A42.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"66694456\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"image2017-7-7 16:41:42.png\" data-base-url=\"https://confluence\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"66694463\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"13\" /></span>\r\n\r\n<em>These are results of an example test run:</em>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image\" src=\"https://confluence/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-7%2016%3A42%3A27.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" data-image-src=\"/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-7%2016%3A42%3A27.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"66694457\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"image2017-7-7 16:42:27.png\" data-base-url=\"https://confluence\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"66694463\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"13\" /></span>\r\n<h2 id=\"TeamFoundationServer:ASolutionforContinuousIntegrationandDeployment-ContinuousDeployment\">Continuous Deployment</h2>\r\nOur build system supports a key component of CD, the ability to automatically push your build to your environments. There are two ways to do this. The first is a module that we created in TFS. It allows for an automatic release of the build through Release Management. Alternatively, we can let TFS take care of the release process by linking a build to a release template. When using TFS, you can deploy not only to Windows machines, but also to Mac or Linux machines.\r\n\r\n<em>This is the module that allows connection to Release Management:</em>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-size\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image\" src=\"https://confluence/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-10%2015%3A38%3A7.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" height=\"400\" data-image-src=\"/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-10%2015%3A38%3A7.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"66694458\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"image2017-7-10 15:38:7.png\" data-base-url=\"https://confluence\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"66694463\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"13\" /></span>\r\n\r\n<em>This is an example of linking a TFS release to a build:</em>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-size\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image\" src=\"https://confluence/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-10%2015%3A38%3A54.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" height=\"400\" data-image-src=\"/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-10%2015%3A38%3A54.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"66694459\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"image2017-7-10 15:38:54.png\" data-base-url=\"https://confluence\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"66694463\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"13\" /></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOverall, TFS provides a very powerful and extendable build system. While it has many out-of-the-box features and a large offering of community modules, it also provides tools for you to create your own modules.┬áAlong with this, it supports key CI features such as automated builds, automated testing, and automated deployments. It is also cross-platform, so you can use it to build and deploy to any environment that you need. Everyday, it continues to evolve. Features are regularly being released, and the community continues to make modules. As more is added, it becomes a more powerful and robust CI/CD tool. If you\'re feeling adventurous, jump in and explore what it has to offer!','All About Containers','','inherit','closed','closed','','48-revision-v1','','','2017-08-31 18:29:21','2017-08-31 18:29:21','',48,'http://localhost:8000/?p=52',0,'revision','',0),(53,1,'2017-08-31 18:29:49','2017-08-31 18:29:49','Currently, Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Deployment (CD) are hot topics, especially within Quicken Loans. Engineers want a tool that can build their code, run tests, then deploy automatically. They also want to be able to integrate their tools of choice into the CI/CD pipeline. Many engineers donΓÇÖt realize that we\'ve been using a tool that has provided these features for a very long time, the Team Foundation Server (TFS).\r\n\r\nTFS provides features that extend across the whole software development life cycle. From a planning perspective, it provides requirements management along with project management (think work items, stories, etc.). From the development side of things, it provides source control, along with an extendable, automated build and deploy system. Finally, from a Quality Assurance (QA) perspective, there is a full testing platform, including test case management and test running capabilities.\r\n\r\nNow that we\'ve covered the basics of TFS, we can explore how it provides the CI and CD features that engineers are looking for.\r\n<h2 id=\"TeamFoundationServer:ASolutionforContinuousIntegrationandDeployment-Build\" class=\"wiki-content\">Build</h2>\r\nThe build system within TFS is very powerful. It is a cross-platform build system, and consists of \"modules\" that perform specific tasks as part of your build. There are dozens of out-of-the-box build modules including MSBuild, Ant, Maven, Guip, Gradle, Make, and more. Outside of build modules, there are also modules for performing general tasks like running unit tests, running scripts, security testing, and publishing build artifacts. Since it is cross-platform, we can run modules on any platform. For example, you can run batch and PowerShell scripts for a Windows build, and also run shell scripts for a Linux build. This also means that you can build multiple types of applications. You can build .NET applications, Java (including Android apps), Xcode workspaces, Xamarin, and more.\r\n\r\n<em>Below is a sample of the task catalog that contains build modules:</em>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-size\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image\" src=\"https://confluence/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-6%2011%3A28%3A45.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" alt=\"task list\" width=\"391\" height=\"400\" data-image-src=\"/download/attachments/66694463/image2017-7-6%2011%3A28%3A45.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1499796875000&amp;api=v2\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"66694454\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"image2017-7-6 11:28:45.png\" data-base-url=\"https://confluence\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"66694463\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"13\" /></span>\r\n\r\nDespite the build system containing many modules, there are s